My child came out to me as trans about a month ago, and I agree, every situation is different. I grew up very much feeling that I had the lgbtq's back. As a teenager I boycotted a local movie theater because they wouldn't let us see an (unrated) comedy about lesbians because we were underage. I did my senior high school project on crossdressers. When one of my girls came out to me as bi (age 10), I celebrated her bravery in speaking about something difficult. When my older daughter came out as lesbian and later genderfluid, I was likewise relatively unfazed. However, when that same genderfluid daughter eventually came out to us as trans, suddenly I found myself confused and a bit ashamed of my own reaction. As well as one of acceptance and unconditional love, it was also one of loss and conflicting emotions. I never would have thought pronouns would make a big deal, but for some reason they're a mental hurdle that's been difficult to get used to. Also, I spent a long time and a lot of love picking out an original and feminine name, and now he goes by the commonest male name I can think of. Probably the hardest thing has been trying to understand the identity of someone who grew up female and identifies as male. It  threw me into a state of reexamination of what parts of his personality were really his and which parts were based on my perception of him. As an ally to the community, I felt like a failure for not being able to understand or identify. One of my friends gave me sh*t about my mixed reactions too which hurt me. It's different when it's a child you've borne than when you're speaking about a community at large. My family is super supportive too, which is great, but to a degree I want to fight to defend his honor -- but there's no one among my family to fight. It's another part of why it's been hard -- trying to fight an imaginary enemy. I know he's run into some hard times with his peers, and that's not good, and I get that, but nothing within the family. I asked him to talk with me the other day about being trans, and he rolled his eyes and said, "yeah, Mom, I know what you're going to say, that you love me and support me no matter what." I said, "yes, but you have to understand it's hard for me, harder than I  thought, and I hope you'll forgive me if I hurt your feelings or don't understand. I will do my best, and of course I do love and support you, but I'm having a harder time dealing with it than I thought I would." To both my ex-husband and me, he has said that he'll go back to being our little girl if we want him to, which honestly has made the situation even more difficult. So I'm learning everything I can.

As a cis, the best way that one of my friend (who is trans) explained it to me was: Imagine that you woke up the next morning with "male genitals" (if you're a cis woman) or "female genitals" (if you're a cis man). You look in the mirror and the body that you see doesn't match who you are. Now imagine that you went to the store and the cashier said, "thank you ma'am" or "thank you sir" and you knew they were wrong but nobody else saw you the way that you felt. And you had to navigate through life with people assuming you were something that you weren't. Essentially, if you woke up looking like a female then you wouldn't suddenly identify as a woman; you'd still be the same person. Now I've educated myself more on the subject and know that there's a lot more to it then that and that I will never completely understand but it was a breakthrough for me when it came to beginning to understand more.

Some criticism: I agree with your general ideas but there are a few scenes I disagree with, or rather, would have worded differently. For example, the use of "feel", "identify", "percieve", "gender identity" and "gender". It's best not to use the words identify and feel because we don't identify or feel a gender. The only way you can feel male or female is the roles assigned, however we can generally "feel" that our sex is wrong, which is actually just dysphoria. I think it's best to not use the words gender or gender identity either  because they both refer to the social and cultural roles assigned to men and women, gender identity being which role you identify with the most and how you express that. As trans people, we know that this is not the case for us but we have been lead to believe that gender and gender identity is when our outside doesn't match the inside. However this description is inaccurate as gender has never referred to this, it's always referred to the social aspect. It would be much better to state that our sex does not match with who we are inside, hence dysphoria rather than our "gender". As you stated, this has nothing to do with gender non-conformity and by using the term gender, it just reinforces the idea that if you do not conform to your gender role, you are trans.

I really like the sweater analogy when it comes to explaining how you know you're trans. It goes as follows: you're shopping with someone (this person represents society). You're in the changing room with them, and they're forcing a sweater on you, but it's way too small, and way too thin. You've been eyeing another sweater the whole trip, and it looks wonderful, but Society is telling you that you can't have that one. You decide to try it on anyway, and it's comfy and warm and fits just right. Society is telling you over and over that it looks ugly and isn't right and it's too expensive and you might change your mind, but you buy it anyway, and it's absolutely perfect.

That's what being trans is like. I just want to leave maybe a more nuanced comment about what you said about "it's when your outside doesn't match your inside" : as a trans person, i believe that my outside matches my inside, because I'm non binary and my body isn't inherently gendered (since gender is a social construct). It's society that associate my appearance with being a woman, but my body is not inherently "a woman's body"; it's just a body. And this association body <=> woman makes me feel bad and feel dysphoria. That's just my experience, and not every trans person feel this way, but I wanted to highlight this as the narrative of "born in the wrong body" is in my opinion a simplistic and reductive description of being trans and I wouldn't recommend to use it even in trans 101 as it perpetuates cissexist ideas about bodies (I'm not saying that Chase said "born in the wrong body" I'm just giving more details because "your inside doesn't match your outside" could easily make people think "oh they're born in the wrong body then").

There are things i don't understand with gender dysphoria and the transpeople. 
Why do transmen, all around the world, transition into what the west think a 20th or 21st century male is like? There are many cultures around the world where males wear what would be considered women's clothing by the west. Even ancient greek and roman men would wear what normally a woman would wear today. I've tried to search for a transmen with long hair on youtube but couldn't find one. They all have short hair. Men do grow their hair. Men have always had long hair. So why do all transmen have short hair and facial hair (a small amount don't have facial hair), at least on youtube? It's like they are trying to become a caricatural male. No variation whatsoever. 
Even with choosing names. What if names, from the beginning of time, were neutral. A name won't make someone become more male or female. A feminine gay man with a male name will still be gay and feminine.
Now transpeople have gender dysphoria and once they transition, the GD goes away (i get this from a trans who commented on another video). How does the GD go away? Your body will always be what it was at birth, even with cosmetic surgeries. Not even CRISPR can do something about that (could be wrong). So how does transitioning help? From my point of view, it's like playing pretend. Cause for a transmen, for eg, just having short hair is the same as going through a wardrobe change, taking hormones, having surgeries. The birth body will remain the birth body. Same applies for transwomen. Normally the GD shouldn't not go away. And if it does, transpeople might as well have tried living as biological males or females and follow a therapy for the GD.
Most trans people are born in a healthy and normal body. Yet it's the body that has to change, through a painful process, to fit what's in the mind. It seems really extreme. What if tomorrow, someone came up with a pill to totally cure gender dysphoria? No more feeling being in the wrong body. Would trans people take it? Wouldn't that be the reasonable choice?
I'm trying to UNDERSTAND, NOT ATTACK AND HURT, the trans community. So if you reply to my comment, please be civil.

The person who thinks 10 inches is possible with phallo is seriously misinformed and clueless about male biology. The average biological penis is like 5.8 inches or maybe even 5.6.
Having 8 inches is incredibly unlikely, and the phallus cannot shrink and get erect (without an implanted device), it is constantly the same size. You would need a permanently stiff rod in it, so constantly having 7 stiff inches either angled up, or down just wouldn't be practical. It would likely result in the rod splitting through the flesh or corroding the flesh around it. Or, the other option is the pump device, which has loads of flaws as well. That doesn't remove the 7 inches of flesh that you constantly have to flop around so it is in a comfortable position.

Erectile implants have to be replaced, and it has a high risk of infection, to the point that the entire phallus needs to be amputated.
Phalloplasty horror stories are worth looking into before you consider getting it. It most likely, is not worth it.

I'm for sure getting a bilateral orchiectomy though. Most Drs recommend it due to being on t blockers too long causes blood clots & organ failure. So once testosterone is premanently gone you can lower estrogen & go off blockers. Less risks!  It's been a long courageous battle for me but I'm on the transition path. Thanks to love & support from my wonderful family & amazing medical care. We all only live one life. It's important to be happy, healthy & comfortable in our own bodies.
The truth is there is no right or wrong way to transition. Society places labels & expectations on trans people.

A friend of mine had gender reassignment surgery about 4 years ago and she is loving it. I watched her go through so much research, therapy, consultations, and years of saving up money to see her dream of becoming her true self. Just going through the beginning stages, hormone therapy, implants, some minor facial reconstruction to give her face a more feminine appearance, her personality and attitude shined even brighter. I also loved the fact that she has so much support from her family friends. We also worked together, and a huge to do was made when she came back to work (after taking a mental health leave to get a handle on what she would be dealing with) meetings were held in each department with our supervisors explaining what transgender meant, that she would start using the woman's bathroom, etc etc. For the most part everyone was like ok why are we even having these meetings and making a big deal about her, then there were a few ignorant people that made their comments and I made sure to try to educate them. I even asked her to come up to my department to introduce herself, and she was very open to answering anyone's curiosity questions. That hair though...... it is definitely you!

Hi Gigi, it good that you not do it when you not feel ready as this will change forever. I am from Thailand and work in plastic and medical in Thailand. I don't know which Dr, you went to... As thailand for surgery that will be under GA you should have it done in hospital not at clinic if you are went to clinic, some surgeon will have their consultation at the clinic and have surgery in private hospital and the service quite good. :) 
Also most surgeon who work with foreign client many of them have very good English. You don't even have to call them, all you need is sending them email, but for SRS it is required face to face consultation.. also first thing before the procedure start on discussion, our partner surgeon always ask for the letter from your psychologist. I work with many surgeon in Thailand.. And if you have surgeon done in The place like Bumrungrad or BDMS hospital group there is nothing to complain. There is few specialist in Bangkok who perform in hospital and also in Phuket.  
In Thailand if you do surgery under GA it will required a night stay in hospital, except you went to dodgy clinic.... and I dont recommend to do that.  Also here if you do surgery in hospital you will be ask to pay for your surgery before you going to surgery, full amount there is no down payment. :)

I fear that while trying to portray your experience as transparent you neglect to inform the viewer on the full risks of what you're doing to yourself and your body. You're not telling the full story, and portraying it from the perspective of almost pseudo encouragement by saying it was the answer to your dismorphia. Your complaints are about your innate masculine features and by complaining about what the therapy did in a damaging way, it insinuates how that damage helped correct your look to be more feminine. Not everyone will have the same feminizing effects taking hormone therapy, some men might just get male pattern baldness and more visceral fat, some men might end up losing the cartilage inbetween their bones. Just because you ended up getting fat in "all the right places" for your goals doesn't mean that will happen to all. To pretend that the side effects of your treatment happened as they should and that all hormone replacement and therapy will lead to desired results is a lie at best, and intentionally misleading at worst.

You're pretending that the few things you do complain about are the biggest risks, yet you refrain from sharing any other traumatic responses to hormone therapy like astigmatism, infertility, bone density degregation, increase in cancer risk, damaged immune system, hypo/hyper thyroidism and blood disease.

Like so many others in this community, your explanation of your therapy is completely focused on the visual and cosmetic, rather than the intrinsic and internal affects done to you. You're playing a game with your words, and while you may not intend it, these are the consequences. You are so, so articulate. Thank you for the work you did in making this video and for making a person questioning their gender not feel out of place because I haven't necessarily seen someone with the same exact story as mine. I haven't really seriously thought about my gender before I guess... But suddenly I've started experiencing gender dysphoria at the age of 21 while never experiencing it before at any point in my life that I can remember, and now I'm looking back and like my favorite songs in middle school were Androgyny and Cherry Lips by Garbage, which both definitely deal with trans themes imo. I'm thinking maybe I just never seriously thought about my gender before until like a month ago so I never really thought it might not be best for me? Until I started thinking about how much better I'd feel in social situations being a woman... So I think I've always had the euphoria (when I was little I used to 'play ballet' in my room with piano music), I just never put two and two together that what I really enjoyed in doing those activities  was the idea of filling a (very stereotypical) social role of what I thought it meant to be a woman back then. As I grew up those activities were kind of stamped out of me by my family, relatives, and church, so I really honestly forgot I could experience those feelings because I was always perceived as being a man. I just always felt like there was something missing, I mean if I am a man (ugh I hate this process) then I'm gay, so I thought that that was what I was missing, but I still would just have these deep-seated angers at random points about having to engage with strangers and friends as a man in every social situation and it was getting tiresome. I shoved it down as far as I could and would hang out with pretty bro-ish people (even though I didn't act super broey myself), even during college tho I expanded my circles to more feminine-presenting people then and realized that I was missing out on a lot of fun just being able to be myself 100%.

Now two things are making me start to experience this childhood gender euphoria I almost forgot about... 1. is my hair. The more I've grown it out the more I feel... just... right. Like I never noticed there was something off but now that I'm experiencing it there is something definitely off. And 2. is trying makeup. Once I started putting it on (with some friends) I just felt like this intense happiness that I was doing something to present as more feminine. Since these things are happening that might be why I'm "suddenly" experiencing dysphoria?

And I'm not even sure still if I am a woman 100%

On names: I've seen a lot of the older trans people (like me) change to something either close to their name, or with the same initials, along those lines. For instance, I know I Maureen who is now Mor, a Brian Laurence who is Brenda Lauren. With me, Christopher changed to Christyanne allows me to still use Chris, a name that I'm used to, and I'm too old and crotchety to get used to a new one.
